Hypothesis Testing and Regression

Introduction

In this discussion, we will show some of the basic statistical tools and parametric tests:

  • T test for difference of mean for two groups
  • ANOVA test for difference of means of multiple groups
  • Chi-Square test for independence
  • Simple Linear Regression

Other tests will also be mentioned, since these are prerequisites to show that the dataset follows the assumptions of the mentioned statistical tests:

  • Test for Normality (Shapiro-Wilk or Kolmogorov-Smirnov)
  • Test for Homoscedasticity or Equality of Variance (Ftest, Levenes test, Bartletts test, or Fligner-Killeen Test)

Plots will also be used to visualize data prior to testing

  • Histogram to show shape of distribution
  • Boxplot to show central tendency and dispersion
  • Scatter plot to show correlation and (linear) relationship between two variables

These are just the basics and just the application in R. You should know beforehand how and when to use these statistical tests.

Basic Hypothesis Tests

T Test

The mtcars dataset contains data on various aspects of 32 different automobile models, including their miles per gallon (mpg), number of cylinders, horsepower, and other factors.

Suppose we want to compare the consumption in miles per gallon (mpg) of cars with different numbers of cylinders = 4 and 6 using a t-test. Take note that the number of cylinders is converted to factor

mtcars_sub <- subset(mtcars, cyl %in% c(4, 6))%>%
    select(mpg, cyl)%>%
    mutate(cyl = as.factor(cyl))
mtcars_sub
summary(mtcars_sub)
##       mpg        cyl   
##  Min.   :17.80   4:11  
##  1st Qu.:21.00   6: 7  
##  Median :22.15         
##  Mean   :23.97         
##  3rd Qu.:26.98         
##  Max.   :33.90

Lets obtain the mean and standard deviation of mpg by cyl.

summary_stat <- mtcars_sub%>%
    group_by(cyl)%>%
    summarize(mean(mpg),
              sd(mpg))
summary_stat

Visualization

From the above visualizations, we can see the the average miles per gallon consumption is higher for vehicles with 4 cylinders than with 6 cylinders.

Test for Normality

Shapiro-Wilk test for normality have a null assumption that your current data follows Normal distribution. Rejecting the null means that your data does not follow a normal distribution. To summarize:

\[ Ho: \text{Data follows Normal Distribution} \]

\[ Ha: \text{Data does not follow Normal Distribution} \]

The shapiro.test function of the stats library can help us test normality of a data stored in a vector.

shapiro.test(mtcars_sub$mpg)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  mtcars_sub$mpg
## W = 0.90193, p-value = 0.06209

However, the assumption of T test is that data from EACH group is normal, not when data is aggregated. Hence, results from the chunk above is not directly useful.

Let us use the shapiro_test of the rstatix package to test normality of the variable mpg grouped according to cyl.

mtcars_sub %>% group_by(cyl) %>%
    summarize(shapiro_test(mpg))

If the p-value for each group is >0.05, then data from each group follows normality.

Note: Just a warning on the use of normality tests, when sample size is low, it is very likely that the null assumption of normality will not be rejected. For such cases, just use logic and context to reason that the generation of your data is a Gaussian (normal) process.

Test for Homoscedasticity

The var.test performs an F test to compare variances of two samples from normal population.

var.test(mpg ~ cyl, mtcars_sub, 
         alternative = "two.sided")
## 
##  F test to compare two variances
## 
## data:  mpg by cyl
## F = 9.6261, num df = 10, denom df = 6, p-value = 0.01182
## alternative hypothesis: true ratio of variances is not equal to 1
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##   1.762592 39.198688
## sample estimates:
## ratio of variances 
##           9.626086

Performing the T test

Lets perform a two-tailed t-test assuming unequal variance.

t.test(mpg ~ cyl, data = mtcars_sub, var.equal = F)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  mpg by cyl
## t = 4.7191, df = 12.956, p-value = 0.0004048
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group 4 and group 6 is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##   3.751376 10.090182
## sample estimates:
## mean in group 4 mean in group 6 
##        26.66364        19.74286

If we want to perform a one-tailed test (with direction of inequality), it is important that you know which is on the left hand side (LHS) and right hand side (RHS) of the inequality (unlike if the alternative is just \(\neq\) ). To know which is on the LHS or RHS, check the order of levels. This works even if the factor variable is unordered.

levels(mtcars_sub$cyl)
## [1] "4" "6"

For this case, the first argument in the inequality is the group with 4 cylinders. That is:

  • alternative = "two.sided": mpg with 4 cylinders \(\neq\) mpg with 6 cylinders
  • alternative = "less" : mpg with 4 cylinders \(<\) mpg with 6 cylinders
  • alternative = "greater" : mpg with 4 cylinders \(>\) mpg with 6 cylinders

ANOVA

For the PlantGrowth dataset, we want to know if there are differences in weight of the plants under different treatment conditions.

PlantGrowth
summary(PlantGrowth)
##      weight       group   
##  Min.   :3.590   ctrl:10  
##  1st Qu.:4.550   trt1:10  
##  Median :5.155   trt2:10  
##  Mean   :5.073            
##  3rd Qu.:5.530            
##  Max.   :6.310
PlantGrowth %>% group_by(group) %>%
    summarize(mean(weight), sd(weight))

Visualization

PlantGrowth %>%
    ggplot(aes(x = group, fill = group, y = weight))+
    geom_boxplot()

Test for Normality

library(rstatix)
PlantGrowth %>% group_by(group) %>%
    summarize(shapiro_test(weight))

Levenes Test for Homoscedasticity

If the number of groups is greater than 2, we use Levenes test instead of F test. We may only use this test for equality of variance if the samples are from normally distributed populations. Null hypothesis for this test is that the variances are equal.

library(car)
leveneTest(weight ~ group, PlantGrowth)

Performing the ANOVA

Finally, we perform the anova using the aov function and the results can be shown by the summary function.

anova1 <- aov(weight ~ group, PlantGrowth)
summary(anova1)
##             Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)  
## group        2  3.766  1.8832   4.846 0.0159 *
## Residuals   27 10.492  0.3886                 
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Post-hoc test

A significant one-way ANOVA is generally followed up by post-hoc tests to perform multiple pairwise comparisons between groups. One method is Tukeys Honestly Significant Difference Test.

TukeyHSD(anova1)
##   Tukey multiple comparisons of means
##     95% family-wise confidence level
## 
## Fit: aov(formula = weight ~ group, data = PlantGrowth)
## 
## $group
##             diff        lwr       upr     p adj
## trt1-ctrl -0.371 -1.0622161 0.3202161 0.3908711
## trt2-ctrl  0.494 -0.1972161 1.1852161 0.1979960
## trt2-trt1  0.865  0.1737839 1.5562161 0.0120064

Other common post-hoc tests are Bonferroni, Scheffe, and Tukey-Kramer, each has different assumption on distribution and sample sizes. In Stat 148, you will know which test is appropriate based on your data to balance power and robustness of the test.

\(\chi^2\) test for Independence

The TitanicSurvival dataset in the library carData provides information on the passengers of the Titanic, including whether they survived or not, their class, age, and sex.

library(carData)
TitanicSurvival

Recall the null hypothesis of a Chi-square test for independence:

\[ Ho: \text{No association between the two categorical variables} \]

Suppose we want to know if the survival of an individual is dependent on their sex.

tab <- table(TitanicSurvival$survived, TitanicSurvival$sex)
tab
##      
##       female male
##   no     127  682
##   yes    339  161

Visualization

A mosaic plot is a proportional display for a n-way table.

library(ggmosaic)
## Warning: package 'ggmosaic' was built under R version 4.2.3
ggplot(TitanicSurvival) +
  geom_mosaic(aes(x = product(sex), fill = survived))
## Warning: `unite_()` was deprecated in tidyr 1.2.0.
## Please use `unite()` instead.
## This warning is displayed once every 8 hours.
## Call `lifecycle::last_lifecycle_warnings()` to see where this warning was generated.

Peforming Chi-square test for independence

Let us perform a Chi-square test using the chisq.test of the stats package.

The output of the chi-squared test will include the chi-squared statistic, degrees of freedom, and the p-value. If the p-value is less than the significance level (usually 0.05), we can reject the null hypothesis that the two variables are independent.

Note that if the contingency table is 2x2, Yates continuity correction is enabled by default. You can disable this by setting correct = F.

chisq.test(TitanicSurvival$survived, TitanicSurvival$sex)
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction
## 
## data:  TitanicSurvival$survived and TitanicSurvival$sex
## X-squared = 363.62, df = 1, p-value < 2.2e-16

What is the conclusion?

Simple Linear Regression Models

Suppose we want to find the linear relationship of budget on education and income per capita of the states.

ggplot(Anscombe, aes(x = education, y = income))+
    geom_point()+
    geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = F)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

The correlation of income and education is 0.66, which shows a moderate to strong positive correlation. The plot above visualizes this relationship. Let us perform a linear regression to quantify the relationship.

mod1 <- lm(income ~ education, data = Anscombe)

Multiple Linear Regression

We have shown that urban ratio and budget for education both have linear relationship with income per capita. However, the models (with only 1 independent variable each) are not sufficient enough to explain the variation of income, shown in the values of R^2.

ggplot(Anscombe, aes(y = income, x = education, color = urban))+
    geom_point()+
    scale_color_viridis_c() # viridis is a color palette

We not fit the following line on the data:

\[ Y_{income} = \beta_0 +\beta_1 X_{education} + \beta_2 X_{urban} +\varepsilon \]

mod3 <- lm(income ~ education + urban, data = Anscombe)
summary(mod3)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = income ~ education + urban, data = Anscombe)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -835.77 -170.76   13.54  157.23  829.74 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) 640.0676   233.7516   2.738  0.00864 ** 
## education     6.3094     0.9463   6.668 2.38e-08 ***
## urban         2.0265     0.2904   6.977 7.97e-09 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 299.9 on 48 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.7248, Adjusted R-squared:  0.7133 
## F-statistic:  63.2 on 2 and 48 DF,  p-value: 3.568e-14

Notice how the value of \(R^2\) increased.

Prediction

Using the original data, we obtain the fitted values of income from the model (mod3) with education and urban as predictors. We use the predict function to predict value of the dependent variable y given the values of the regressors. resid is the difference between the observed values and the fitted values.

fitted3 <- predict(mod3, Anscombe)
resid3 <- resid(mod3)
data.frame(Anscombe$income, fitted3,resid3)

In terms of notation, a fitted value is denoted as \(\hat{y}_i\) where \(i\) is a specific observation (state).

Now, suppose we want to predict the income of 2 new states, and data for education, young ratio, and urban ratio are available. Data is stored in dataframe new_states.

new_state1 <- c(education = 190, young = 350, urban = 500)
new_state2 <- c(education = 300, young = 275, urban = 250)
new_states <- data.frame(rbind(new_state1, new_state2))
new_states

Note that the new data frame new_states has the same columns required for the predictors stored in the lm object mod3 (which are education and urban). We can predict the expected income of the two new states given the predictors.

predict(mod3, new_states)
## new_state1 new_state2 
##   2852.086   3039.508
